  abstract = {{$<$}p{$><$}strong class="journal-contentHeaderColor"{$>$}Abstract.{$<$}/strong{$>$} Nitrogen oxides ({$<$}math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" id="M2" display="inline" overflow="scroll" dspmath="mathml"{$><$}mrow class="chem"{$><$}msub{$><$}mi mathvariant="normal"{$>$}NO{$<$}/mi{$><$}mi{$>$}x{$<$}/mi{$><$}/msub{$><$}mo{$>\equiv<$}/mo{$><$}mi mathvariant="normal"{$>$}NO{$<$}/mi{$><$}mo{$>$}+{$<$}/mo{$><$}msub{$><$}mi mathvariant="normal"{$>$}NO{$<$}/mi{$><$}mn mathvariant="normal"{$>$}2{$<$}/mn{$><$}/msub{$><$}/mrow{$><$}/math{$>$}{$<$}svg:svg xmlns:svg="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="85pt" height="13pt" class="svg-formula" dspmath="mathimg" md5hash="f610f94fb6c20199e6f641866e657b1f"{$><$}svg:image xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="acp-18-17017-2018-ie00001.svg" width="85pt" height="13pt" src="acp-18-17017-2018-ie00001.png"/{$><$}/svg:svg{$>$}) in the upper troposphere (UT) have a large impact on global tropospheric ozone and OH (the main atmospheric oxidant). New cloud-sliced observations of UT NO\textsubscript{2} at 450\textendash 280\&thinsp;hPa ({$\sim$}6\textendash 9\&thinsp;km) from the Ozone Monitoring Instrument (OMI) produced by NASA and the Royal Netherlands Meteorological Institute (KNMI) provide global coverage to test our understanding of the factors controlling UT NO\textsubscript{\emph{x}}. We find that these products offer useful information when averaged over coarse scales ({$<$}math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" id="M6" display="inline" overflow="scroll" dspmath="mathml"{$><$}mrow{$><$}mn mathvariant="normal"{$>$}20{$<$}/mn{$><$}msup{$><$}mi/{$><$}mo{$>\circ<$}/mo{$><$}/msup{$><$}mo{$>\times <$}/mo{$><$}mn mathvariant="normal"{$>$}32{$<$}/mn{$><$}msup{$><$}mi/{$><$}mo{$>\circ<$}/mo{$><$}/msup{$><$}/mrow{$><$}/math{$>$}{$<$}svg:svg xmlns:svg="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="46pt" height="11pt" class="svg-formula" dspmath="mathimg" md5hash="55f159cafb79d8ecf49805e6c5c5fba2"{$><$}svg:image xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="acp-18-17017-2018-ie00002.svg" width="46pt" height="11pt" src="acp-18-17017-2018-ie00002.png"/{$><$}/svg:svg{$>$}, seasonal), and that the NASA product is more consistent with aircraft observations of UT NO\textsubscript{2}. Correlation with Lightning Imaging Sensor (LIS) and Optical Transient Detector (OTD) satellite observations of lightning flash frequencies suggests that lightning is the dominant source of NO\textsubscript{\emph{x}} to the upper troposphere except for extratropical latitudes in winter. The NO\textsubscript{2} background in the absence of lightning is 10\textendash 20\&thinsp;pptv. We infer a global mean NO\textsubscript{\emph{x}} yield of 280{$\pm$}80\&thinsp;moles per lightning flash, with no significant difference between the tropics and midlatitudes, and a global lightning NO\textsubscript{\emph{x}} source of 5.9{$\pm$}1.7\&thinsp;Tg\&thinsp;N\&thinsp;a\textsuperscript{-1}. There is indication that the NO\textsubscript{\emph{x}} yield per flash increases with lightning flash footprint and with flash energy.{$<$}/p{$>$}},
